@NODE "mail_14" " After high demand ;-) CreateNewProc_ "
From: amorel <amorel@...>
Date: 02-25-03 18:18:40
Subject: @{b}After high demand ;-) CreateNewProc_@{ub}

There was some talk about starting a new process on this list, in the Summer.
I checked the archives as I had to do this. A full solution wasn`t given, but
from a mix of emails on different subjects(about cia interrupts for example) I
did find a solution:

****************

some code
....
taskend.b=NFalse ;this variable can be set to true to quit the process
taglist.l=0 ;this is the taglist variable

;somewhere before mainloop starts
MOVE.l a5,globbase ;reserve global variable base for new process

NResetTagList #NP_Entry, ?wap
   NAddTag #NP_Name, "Whoppa"
   NAddTag #NP_Priority, 127 ;this is highest priority, I need that but 
                             ;normally you want something lower ;-)
*proces.Process=CreateNewProc_(taglist)
if *process=0 then it$="has failed"
....
more code

;this is the code for the new process, it has name: Whoppa

.wap:
   MOVEM.l a0-a6/d0-d7,-(a7) ;save registers
   MOVE.l globbase(pc),a5 ;global variable base
   sec.l=0
   Repeat
      uselessvar.b=NTrue
      ....
      more code ;probably some delaying code if not anything cpu intensive
                ;needs to be done(an undelayed loop at priority 127 tends
                ;to make your computer very unresponsive ;-)
   until taskend=ntrue ;this will be set to true in the main process
   MOVEM.l (a7)+,a0-a6/d0-d7 ;restore registers
   RTS
   globbase: Ds.l 1
return

****************

Most of this I figured out myself with some pointers found in various 
emails.

The asm code i ripped from an email by David McMinn about how to use blitz
code in an interrupt handler. So this should work with that too and similar
things.

This does work and is far cleaner than using the execute command. Thilo is
using that solution, but then you need an external binary(or maybe incbin`ed?)
and if that has been deleted or whatever, then you have problems.

I gave it priority 127, that makes it certain that the process will always 
run uniterrupted by other things except ofcourse hardware interrupts. I
could make a similar interrupt handler(I think) but interrupt handlers have
the ristriction you can`t do any intuition and i/o stuff etc and in the new
process one can happily use every os and blitz command. Maybe I`ll
give an option to switch from one to the other method. I`ve yet to get this
process to slowed down or so, so it is very "stable" so to say.

Hope this might help anyone.

Regards


