On Wed, Feb 26, 2003 at 11:32:47AM +0100, Thilo Köhler wrote:
> 1) For some reason I am not allowed to call functions and statements.
> Any idea why ? I always get "Out of Stack Space" error when the debugger
> is switched on. Maybe it is only a problem of the debugger ?
> For some strange reason the debugger is sometimes put into Trace mode.

Well the debugger does not work with the child process and it is advisable to switch 
off the debugger right before the child process code starts. It is hard to debug 
code without it, but there is no other way. Alternatively you can code requesters 
showing vars etc at crucial places where you suspect problems etc.  You should be 
able to use functions etc, but perhaps you may write functions in the child process` 
code instead. And here sometimes the debugger goes into trace mode also, mostly if 
sth triggered it, sth went wrong or whatever. Ignore it, a side effect of using 
multithreading I guess.
 
> 2) Some blitz commands, like "Request" have problems when they
> are called parallel. E.g. Allocmem works or variable handling works.
> I think this is a problem of some blitzcommands and this can not be solved.

It`s best to avoid such a thing anyways, as 2 requests from the same app but in 2 
different processes isn`t a good thing for the user :-) Also if the child process 
does any gui stuff things may become tricky, but thats just a result of multitasking 
and all that. Also I forgot to mention, use semaphores at places where the processes 
use shared variables. It`s best to keep it at a minimum but still so that it prevents 
problems. LockBasic and UnlockBasic does this, it locks the other process so use it 
with care or responsiveness goes bad. It`s quite a tricky afair to do that, but if 
you do it carefully and take time to place those commands at the right spots you 
prevent lots of weird problems.

> 3) What about the A4 ? Does it has to be installed in the new process
> as well ?

Hm, not afaik.

> 4) I think it is not neccessary to backup the registers on start of
> the new process. Am I right ?

afaik It is, I took that stuff from David`s example and I assume he knew what he was 
doing :-)

