@NODE "mail_60" " Re: Slider Knobs "
From: David McMinn <dave@...>
Date: 02-27-03 20:21:07
Subject: @{b}Re: Slider Knobs@{ub}

On 27 Feb 2003 at 10:38, Thilo Köhler wrote:

> I have some GTSliders in my GUI. The knobs go very thin
> if I have a larger value range compared to the pixelsize of the slider.
> 
> Q: Is there any way to force the size of the slider knob to a bigger
> size ?

You mean thin in the direction of the movement of the knob? That size is completely under 
the control of gadtools.library AFAIK (since it automatically calculates the size and 
pixel position given the range and numeric position you specify).

Three possible solutions:

1) Manually alter the range if it gets too big, and maintain a variable for the range 
scale. For example, if the range goes over 16000 you may want to set the range to 8000 
and set your scale value to 2. Any value you read from the slider (for the position) you 
would need to multiply by 2. This would also solve the problem of having a slider which 
needs to take values >32767.

2) Use a GTScroller and keep the visible range large compared to the total range of 
values. Of course, you would then have problems selecting all values in your range unless 
you set the maximum value to be (real_numeric_maximum + visible_range). (This one is 
probably my favourite of the three.)

3) Find some other GUI system or a BOOPSI gadget which allows you to set the knob size.

